'''Sagiyama Kofun''' (鷺山古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kokufu Town, Tottori City|ja|鳥取市国府町|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tottori Prefecture|ja|鳥取県|12=draft|12=draft}}. Its shape is a circular tomb (円墳). The kofun is designated as a historic site by Tottori Prefecture.
== Overview == [[File:Sagiyama Kofun (Tottori), 3D-B.jpg|thumb|300px|right|{{center|Overhead view of the stone chamber}}]] [[File:Sagiyama Kofun (Tottori), 3D-N.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Unfolded view of the stone chamber}}]] The Sagiyama Kofun was constructed on a ridge extending southward from Mount Inaba, north of Mount Koshi, in eastern Tottori Prefecture. It was discovered in {{ill|1966|ja|1966年|12=draft|12=draft}} (Showa 41){{Sfn|Machiya Village (Heibonsha)|1992}}{{Sfn|Sagiyama Kofun (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}.
The tumulus has a circular shape, measuring approximately 10 meters in diameter and 2 meters in height{{Sfn|Sagiyama Kofun (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}. The burial facility is a {{ill|yokoana-style stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}, opening to the south. The chamber features a middle-high structure with the central part of the ceiling raised, but the ceiling stones of the main chamber and the dromos are missing{{Sfn|Sagiyama Kofun (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}. The chamber walls are adorned with numerous engraved motifs, including fish, boats, birds, and geometric patterns. Notably, the rear wall of the chamber features a large fish-shaped engraving, measuring 1.2 meters in length, which depicts realistic details such as eyes, mouth, dorsal fin, and tail, likely representing a salmon or trout{{Sfn|Sagiyama Kofun (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}<ref name="Tottori Prefecture"/>. Fish-shaped engravings are also found in {{ill|Kajiyama Kofun|ja|梶山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} and the Soraoyama Kofun Group, but they are rare nationwide, reflecting strong regional characteristics<ref>"Soraoyama Kofun Group" in ''Tottori Prefecture Place Names'', Japanese Historical Place Names Series 32, Heibonsha, 1992.</ref>. The kofun is estimated to have been constructed in the late {{ill|6th century|ja|6世紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, during the later {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}{{Sfn|Sagiyama Kofun (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}.
The kofun was designated as a historic site by Tottori Prefecture in {{ill|1981|ja|1981st year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Showa 56)<ref name="Tottori Prefecture"/>.
<gallery> Sagiyama Kofun (Tottori), genshitsu-1-2.jpg|Main chamber (towards the rear wall) Sagiyama Kofun (Tottori), genshitsu-2-2.jpg|Main chamber (towards the entrance) Sagiyama Kofun (Tottori), sendou-2.jpg|Dromos (towards the entrance) Sagiyama Kofun (Tottori), sendou-1.jpg|Dromos (towards the main chamber) Sagiyama Kofun (Tottori), genshitsu-3.jpg|Engravings on the rear wall of the main chamber (fish-shaped engraving) </gallery>
== Cultural Properties == === Prefectural Designated Cultural Properties === * Historic Site ** Sagiyama Kofun - Designated on November 27, 1981<ref name="Tottori Prefecture">[http://db.pref.tottori.jp/bunkazainavi.nsf/bunkazai_web_view/B8FB4B54B387BC334925796F0007FE5F?OpenDocument Sagiyama Kofun] (Tottori Prefecture Cultural Properties Navigator).</ref>.
